com.appdynamics.instrumentation.sdk.template.async

Class AAsyncExitEnd

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.appdynamics.instrumentation.sdk.ASDKPlugin
      • com.appdynamics.instrumentation.sdk.template.async.AAsyncExitEnd
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IRuleAppliable

    public abstract class AAsyncExitEnd
extends ASDKPlugin
    Extend this object to complete tracking of an async exit point. This plugin should be placed on a method that marks the end of an async exit point such as completion, failure, timeout, etc. and the method should have access to the same object (enforced by Object.equals(Object)) as the method instrumented by AAsyncExitStart had access to. If the method exits with an exception, then the AsyncExitCall will still be completed and this exit call will be marked as Error in snapshots Warning: this plugin must be used with an AAsyncExitStart plugin to properly begin and end an async transaction. Without an AAsyncExitStart plugin this plugin is essentially useless created by haojun.li on 6/28/18

      • getAsyncObject

        public abstract java.lang.Object getAsyncObject(java.lang.Object invokedObject,
                                                java.lang.Object[] paramValues,
                                                java.lang.Object returnValue)
        Gets the Object we will use to match this async exit start to an async exit end. This object must match the object used in AAsyncExitStart.getAsyncObject(Object, Object[], Object) for the async exit to work correctly. If this method returns null then this interceptor will not end any transaction created by AAsyncExitStart. This could result in a memory leak. We will use the Object.equals(Object) and Object.hashCode() to determine equality instead of whether they point to the same object
        Parameters:
        invokedObject - the object the method was invoked in. null for static methods.
        paramValues - An array of the parameters passed to the method.
        returnValue - the return value of the function call ONLY IF getAsyncObjectOnEnd() is true, null if we call this on method begin, or if there is an exception
        Returns:
        an object we will use to match with AAsyncExitStart.getAsyncObject(Object, Object[], Object) to properly end a transaction

      • getAsyncObjectOnEnd

        public final boolean getAsyncObjectOnEnd()
        Tells the agent if it should get the async object at the end of the method. It is possible that some of the paramValues are not fully populated on method begin. This method is unsupported in 4.5.1. This method should always return false, or it could cause memory leaks.
        Returns:
        true if we need to call the getAsyncObject(Object, Object[], Object) on then end of the method, false otherwise.

      • getAsyncObjectOnExeption

        public boolean getAsyncObjectOnExeption()
        Tells the agent if it should get the async object even if an exception occurred during the execution of the method instrumented. By default the agent will try to get the async object even though there was an exception. Override this to false will provide some performance benefit but could potentially create memory leak. Override with caution
        Returns:
        true if the agent should still get the async object and attempt to track this exit call as async exit call

      • addSnapshotData

        public void addSnapshotData(java.lang.Object invokedObject,
                            java.lang.String className,
                            java.lang.String methodName,
                            java.lang.Object[] paramValues,
                            java.lang.Throwable thrownException,
                            java.lang.Object returnValue,
                            ISDKUserContext context,
                            ISDKDataContext dataContext)
                     throws ReflectorException
        This method attempt to add more information as properties into the snapshot. All data should be added into the dataContext object using ISDKDataContext.storeData(String, Object). Information that was stored inside the UserContext (from other SDK calls) can also be access here and put into the DataContext for display in an snapshot.
        Parameters:
        invokedObject - The object the method was invoked on. null for static methods. available at begin/end.
        className - The name of the class this method was called on. available at begin/end.
        methodName - The name of the method invoked. available at begin/end.
        paramValues - An array of the parameters passed to the method. available at begin/end.
        thrownException - The exception thrown by this invocation of the method. null if method exits normally. available ONLY on end.
        returnValue - The return value of the method. null if exception was thrown. available ONLY on end.
        context - The ISDKUserContext that can be used to pass objects between sdk methods.
        dataContext - The map the agent will use to put information into a snapshot. All information is put into the snapshot as a list of key value pair
        Throws:
        ReflectorException - any exceptions will be handled by the agent in logs
